{# FAQ #}
<section class="py-12">
  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4">
    <h2 class="section-heading mb-8">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="space-y-4">
      <details class="card p-5 group" open>
        <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white">
          What visa do I need to work in the UK as a tech professional?
          <i data-lucide="chevron-down" class="w-5 h-5 text-gray-400 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform"></i>
        </summary>
        <p class="mt-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 text-sm leading-relaxed">
          The <strong>Skilled Worker visa</strong> is the main route. You need a job offer from a UK employer with a valid sponsor license, and the role must meet the minimum salary threshold (generally £38,700 or the going rate). Many tech roles are on the shortage occupation list, which can reduce salary requirements. The visa is granted for up to 5 years and is renewable.
        </p>
      </details>
      <details class="card p-5 group">
        <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white">
          What's the average tech salary in the UK?
          <i data-lucide="chevron-down" class="w-5 h-5 text-gray-400 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform"></i>
        </summary>
        <p class="mt-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 text-sm leading-relaxed">
          London tech salaries typically range from £50,000–£75,000 for mid-level engineers, £80,000–£120,000+ for seniors, and higher at top-tier companies. Salaries outside London are generally 15–25% lower but come with significantly lower living costs. Use our <a href="/tools/salary-calculator/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">Salary Calculator</a> for detailed comparisons.
        </p>
      </details>
      <details class="card p-5 group">
        <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white">
          Is London the only option for tech jobs in the UK?
          <i data-lucide="chevron-down" class="w-5 h-5 text-gray-400 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform"></i>
        </summary>
        <p class="mt-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 text-sm leading-relaxed">
          Not at all. Manchester has a rapidly growing tech scene, Edinburgh is a major fintech center, Bristol and Cambridge have strong engineering communities, and many companies now offer remote or hybrid work. While London has the largest concentration of opportunities, other cities offer excellent quality of life at lower costs.
        </p>
      </details>
      <details class="card p-5 group">
        <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white">
          Can I get permanent residency through the Skilled Worker visa?
          <i data-lucide="chevron-down" class="w-5 h-5 text-gray-400 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform"></i>
        </summary>
        <p class="mt-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 text-sm leading-relaxed">
          Yes. After 5 years on a Skilled Worker visa, you can apply for <strong>Indefinite Leave to Remain (ILR)</strong>, which grants permanent residency. You'll need to pass the Life in the UK test and meet English language requirements. After holding ILR for 12 months, you can apply for British citizenship.
        </p>
      </details>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

